Product Description

It only contains basic oscilloscope functions, no fancy functions. The simplicity of the structure and the ease of assembly/operation are the main goals of the design.

  • The heart is ST's Cortex-M3 ARM processor (STM32F103C8).
  • Adopt 2.4 inch TFT LCD (320 X 240 dot matrix, 262K colors) as the display element, displaying clear waveforms.
  • Detailed assembly instructions are provided with troubleshooting guides and illustrations.
  • Source code is also provided to allow users to add their own functions.

Features:

Analog bandwidth: 0-200KHz Sampling rate: 1Msps max Sensitivity: 10mV/Div-5V/Div Sensitivity error: <5% Vertical resolution: 12-bit Time base: 10us/Div-500s/Div Record length: 1024 points Built-in 1KHz /3.3V test signal waveform freeze (HOLD) function is available

9V DC

Supply Current: 120mA

NOTE:

A 9V DC power supply is required. Not included.

Package included:

  • 1 *Digital Oscilloscope Kit
  • 1 * Probe
  • 1 * User Manual(English)

Frequently encountered problems

1. Use voltage problems

The test voltage must be confirmed before the test, otherwise the instrument may be damaged. Regulate DC or AC, the maximum test voltage of 1x probe is 40V.

2. Screen working time

The most likely cause for the screen to stop working is insufficient battery power. Need to replace the standard DC9V power supply for testing.

3. The LCD screen does not display graphics

Please press the reset button to reset the system, and then solder the leads at the test point. Adjust the DC gear. Then adjust the trigger to test in AUTO mode.

4. Calibration probe hook

The test ring can be soldered to the 3.3V test point. Since our product is equipped with a case, the test point cannot be used after the case is installed. This test point can still be used after removing the shell, just clamp it to the board with an alligator clip. The main screen is a screen assembled by the shell, but the physical objects are separated, and can be assembled or not assembled according to your own wishes.

How customer reviews and ratings work

Customer Reviews, including Product Star Ratings help customers to learn more about the product and decide whether it is the right product for them.

To calculate the overall star rating and percentage breakdown by star, we don’t use a simple average. Instead, our system considers things like how recent a review is and if the reviewer bought the item on Amazon. It also analyzed reviews to verify trustworthiness.

Indium
4.0 out of 5 stars Good bit of kit for price
Reviewed in the United Kingdom on October 3, 2021
Verified Purchase
Firstly, It really is complete - I was worried that I might get a kit of parts because the price is so low, and because of the strange 'UNWELDED' comment in the description.

The only incompleteness I've found so far was a missing wire loop on the reference frequency - a bit worrying as it maybe indicates poor quality control. However, that was easily fixed and the board appears to work well.

The design is generic, but this is one of the cheapest assembled versions I've seen (I paid £19.99). It appears to do a good job within the limits of its specification and I would recommend it as a good low cost introduction to using oscilloscopes with the caveat that there is a possibility you might find the odd problem. If you do find a fault there are full instructions for building and testing included so you should be able to fix it easily enough.

Constantine Apollo
2.0 out of 5 stars Not as good as others for this price (would you beleive it!)
Reviewed in the United Kingdom on August 7, 2022
Verified Purchase
Loved that this was so cheap and capable. Real oscilloscopes are many X times more expensive. Obviously this is not as accurate, but I figured it’d be great for educational purposes, and eye candy for synth music creation.
Unfortunately for this unit I bought two similar devices, and compared this one with the similarly priced FNIRSI-138 pro.
My advice is this one is inferior to the 138-pro, that can be had for almost the same price. The refresh rate is so slow that you can see it struggles to keep up with audio signals at longer time settings, and the casing is far more exposed and less compact than the FNIRSI 138-pro. What’s more, for a few extra £ via eBay you can get the 138pro with a built in battery. Either way, it can be powered by usb (5v), which is far more versatile a power requirement than the 9v input required by the DSO 138.
All in all, I have to say you are better going with the FNIRSI 138 pro. It’s 2.5Msps sample rate is worth waiting the extra few days to experience if you want to get it for the same price as this by ordering via eBay instead of Amazon.
